Moving around.

To change which directory you are sitting in, you use the change-directory command, written c-d. On its own it is simple, but a handful of shorthand symbols save you an enormous amount of typing.

Tilde always means your home directory, somewhere like slash home slash ubuntu. A single dot means the directory you are already in. Two dots mean the parent directory, one level up. A single dash is special: it toggles you back to the previous directory you were in, so you can bounce between two places. And a lone slash means the very root of the filesystem.

So change-directory slash e-t-c takes you straight to e-t-c. Change-directory dot dot moves you up one level. Change-directory with nothing after it, or with a tilde, returns you home. And change-directory dash flips you back to wherever you just came from. Whenever you are unsure where you have landed, print working directory will confirm it.

There is one more idea worth pinning down now: the difference between absolute and relative paths. A path that begins with a slash is absolute; it is measured from the root of the filesystem and means the same thing no matter where you are. A path that does not begin with a slash is relative; it is measured from your current location. So if you are sitting in slash var, then change-directory log, with no leading slash, takes you to slash var slash log, while change-directory slash log would try to jump to a top-level log directory entirely.
